  "output": "## Findings\n\nThis is a Python async batch pipeline (fetch → filter → dedup → notify), not a web app — there's no React/frontend here, so that part of the checklist doesn't apply. I focused on the real equivalents: SQLite query patterns, redundant per-item work, and resource handling. Two concrete, worth-fixing issues; a few minor ones.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\nFor every job in the batch, `diff()` runs a separate `SELECT` and then a separate `INSERT`/`UPDATE`. Several fetchers explicitly note boards with \"thousands of roles\" (Amazon, Microsoft, Google, Apple) — so a single scan run can mean thousands of individual SQLite round trips instead of one.\n\n```python\n# store.py — current\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job); self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    else:\n        ...\n```\n\nFix — one batch `SELECT ... WHERE key IN (...)` (chunked for SQLite's variable limit) to build a lookup dict, then loop in Python and `executemany` the unchanged-row touch:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing: dict[str, str] = {}\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 500):\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 500]\n        placeholders = \",\".join(\"?\" * len(chunk))\n        for row in self.conn.execute(\n            f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({placeholders})\", chunk):\n            existing[row[\"key\"]] = row[\"content_hash\"]\n\n    new, changed, touched = [], [], []\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job); self._insert(cur, job, now)\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); self._update(cur, job, now)\n        else:\n            touched.append((now, job.key))\n    if touched:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", touched)\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\n### 2. Redundant computation — `filters.py:11-27` (regex recompiled per job)\n\n`match()` calls `_compile(include)`/`_compile(exclude)` on **every job**, rebuilding the same `re.escape`'d patterns and `re.Pattern` list from scratch each time inside `filter_jobs`'s list comprehension.\n\n```python\n# current — filter_jobs calls match() per job, which re-derives the pattern list every time\nreturn [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=rules.get(\"include_keywords\"), ...)]\n```\n\nFix — compile once outside the loop and pass patterns straight through:\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          exclude: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          locations: list[str] | None = None,\n          cutoff: datetime | None = None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    if max_age := rules.get(\"max_age_days\"):\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = rules.get(\"locations\")\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\n### 3. Missing index — `store.py:127-135` (`added_since`)\n\n`added_since` filters and sorts by `first_seen` (`WHERE first_seen > ? ORDER BY first_seen, company, title`), but the only index is on `company`. As the table grows this becomes a full scan + sort. Add:\n\n```sql\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_jobs_first_seen ON jobs(first_seen);\n```\n\n### Minor / not worth fixing\n\n- **Memory leaks**: this is a short-lived CLI process per invocation (not a server), so classic heap-growth leaks don't really apply. `fetch_all` (`fetchers.py:1126-1147`) correctly closes the `httpx.AsyncClient` it owns in a `finally`. One small gap: `Store.__init__` (`store.py:36-41`) opens the sqlite connection before `_migrate()`/`executescript` run — if either raises, the connection is never closed. Low impact given process lifetime, but a `try/except: self.conn.close(); raise` would close the gap.\n- **Redundant hashing**: `Job.content_hash` (`models.py:66-69`) is a property that re-hashes on every access; it's read twice per new/changed job (`diff()` comparison + `to_row()`). Cheap (short string, sha256) — not worth caching unless profiling shows otherwise.\n- **Per-notifier HTTP clients** (`notify.py`): `notify_slack`/`notify_webhook`/`notify_sms` each do a one-off synchronous `httpx.post(...)`, opening a fresh connection per call. Fine at today's call volume (once per scan run); would only matter if `dispatch()` started firing per-job instead of per-batch.\n- **React re-renders**: N/A — no frontend in this repo.\n\nThe two real fixes (`Store.diff` batching, `filters.match` regex hoisting) are the ones that scale with board size — everything else is noise at this codebase's current call pattern.\n",
